\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator raised concerns regarding Criterion 1 which was judged as not complying with minimum standards. Although the list of modules provided \'2811 Forestry and 9 Wood Science\'29 is comprehensive and covers a broad range of topics\'2C the rules of combination allow students to take either Forest Science  or Wood Products. They can then select a combination of 16 and 32 credit modules to make up the balance of the 120 credits\'2C with a maximum of four 16 credit modules. As the evaluator indicated\'2C this implies that students could complete the qualification in either Forestry or Wood Science\'2C based on the current rules of combination as there is no requirement in the rules of combination to take modules in both fields. The evaluator felt that it does not make sense to name the qualification Forestry and Wood Science under these rules of combination. If the intention is to give students a broad grounding in both Forestry and Wood Science\'2C then the rules of combination must be adjusted accordingly. If the intention is to allow students to specialize in either Forestry or Wood Science\'2C then consideration should be given to offering two parallel qualifications. The rules of combination could still allow for students to take a limited number of modules from the alternate qualification to broaden their background.\line \line Criteria 3 and 4 were also judged as in need of improvement. Based on statements in the submission the evaluator was of the opinion that the academic and support staff complement is of sufficient size\'2C and the ratio of full-time to part-time staff is appropriate\'2C however\'2C inadequate information was provided to assess this. As a public provider\'2C they have signed the declaration.\line \line The Directorate supports the recommendation that the programme be accredited. \line \cell \pard 

